# Accessibility (a11y) Cursor Rules

## Semantic HTML First
- Use native HTML elements: `<button>`, `<a>`, `<input>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`
- Use heading hierarchy: one `<h1>` per page, sequential levels
- Use `<ul>/<ol>` for lists, not divs with custom styles
- Use `<table>` for tabular data, not for layout
- DON'T: Use `<div>` with `onClick` — use `<button>` instead

## ARIA (When HTML Isn't Enough)
- Rule: No ARIA is better than bad ARIA
- Use `aria-label` for elements without visible text
- Use `aria-describedby` for additional descriptions
- Use `aria-live="polite"` for dynamic content updates
- Use `role` attributes only when native HTML doesn't suffice

## Keyboard Navigation
- All interactive elements must be keyboard accessible
- Use logical tab order (don't override with `tabindex` > 0)
- Implement focus management for modals and dialogs
- Show visible focus indicators (never `outline: none` without replacement)
- Support Escape key for closing modals/popups

## Forms
- Every input must have an associated `<label>`
- Group related inputs with `<fieldset>` and `<legend>`
- Provide clear error messages linked to inputs (`aria-describedby`)
- Use `aria-required` or `required` attribute for mandatory fields

## Color & Contrast
- Minimum contrast ratio: 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text
- Don't use color alone to convey information (add icons, text, patterns)
- Support high contrast mode and `prefers-contrast` media query

## Testing
- Test with screen readers: VoiceOver (Mac), NVDA (Windows)
- Use axe-core for automated accessibility testing
- Test keyboard-only navigation for all user flows
- Verify focus management in dynamic content (modals, tabs, menus)
